{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_015YVXhuHDmb9ezVUha1HaFF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior in this document analysis system. The system has three independent AI reviewers running in parallel, with a merge step to combine results.\n\nKey context:\n- Three independent AI reviewers (clause extractor, risk assessor, compliance checker)\n- Each operates independently on the same document\n- Merge step combines outputs and resolves conflicts\n- Need to think about what infrastructure is REALLY needed to catch each failure\n\nLet me work through each behavior systematically:\n\n## Behavior 1: Clause extractor identifies all key terms\n\nWhat could go wrong?\n- The extractor might miss some key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties)\n- This is fundamentally a problem with the AI model's performance - whether a real LLM extracts all terms correctly\n- Could a mock miss this? No - if I mock the extractor to return specific terms, the test passes by definition\n- Does it depend on real LLM output? YES - whether the model actually identifies all terms is non-deterministic and depends on the actual model's capability\n- The failure is: \"real LLM doesn't extract all terms\" or \"real LLM extraction is incomplete for certain contract types\"\n- This is fundamentally an **Agentic** issue because:\n  - A deterministic function that always returns the same output would be Unit\n  - But the actual failure mode is: \"the real AI model fails to identify certain terms\"\n  - You can't mock your way to discovering this - you need real model calls\n  - Running this 100 times might reveal inconsistency\n\nHowever, I need to think carefully: is there a way to catch this at Integration level? \n- If you have a fixed test contract, you could test that the system calls the clause extractor correctly\n- But whether the extractor ACTUALLY identifies all terms is an Agentic property\n- The test description should be: \"verify the clause extractor finds all required terms in diverse contracts\"\n- To really test this, you need real model calls\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The question is: what's the minimum infrastructure needed to catch a REAL failure?\n\n\n- The extractor might not be invoked at all, or results could be ignored entirely - these are Integration failures\n- But the core issue is model performance: whether the LLM actually extracts all terms from simple contracts versus complex ones\n- Catching this requires real LLM calls with diverse contract types to expose where the model struggles\n\nFor confidence levels, Unit tests (0.05) only validate parsing logic, not extraction quality. Integration tests (0.15) might catch if the extractor isn't wired up, but they won't surface AI performance gaps. System tests (0.1) don't apply here since there's no OS or network layer beyond standard API calls. Workflow tests (0.05) aren't relevant - this isn't a multi-step orchestration problem.\n\nThe real failure mode is Agentic (0.65): the model simply doesn't extract all terms reliably, especially from complex contracts. A mock always returns what you program it to, but a real model can miss terms depending on contract complexity and structure. Testing \"identifies all key terms present in the contract\" meaningfully requires actual model calls across varied contract types to expose these gaps. That's the minimum viable test level - 60 points.\n\nFor the risk assessor, the situation mirrors this exactly. The core failure isn't integration wiring - it's that the model fails to recognize problematic language, particularly when it's indirect or euphemistic. You can't discover this through mocks or integration checks. Real failures include: risk policy loading issues (Integration), the assessment not being invoked (Integration), or the model misunderstanding euphemistic language (Agentic). The third one is what actually matters. Testing requires real contracts with subtle risky language and real model calls across different risk policies to expose where the model's understanding breaks down.\n\nFor the compliance checker, similar dynamics apply. The real failure mode is the model's regulatory knowledge being incomplete or jurisdiction-specific - it might handle US requirements fine but struggle with UK law. Beyond basic integration checks for configuration and API calls, the critical test is whether the model accurately determines compliance across different jurisdictions. That's an Agentic-level concern that mocks can't address.\n\nThe merge step presents a different challenge. When reviewers disagree on a clause, the merge logic needs to preserve both assessments rather than dropping one. This is primarily a logic problem - testable with mock reviewer outputs to trigger conflict scenarios. Real failures include the merge incorrectly discarding assessments, failing to handle certain conflict types, or losing findings when reviewers have different confidence levels. The last case depends on actual model outputs to manifest properly.\n\nI can test the merge logic at the integration level using crafted test cases - for instance, having one reviewer flag a clause as \"optional\" while another marks it \"high risk,\" then verifying both assessments appear in the output with proper attribution. However, genuine failures only surface when running actual models, since real outputs might produce unanticipated conflicts, incompatible assessment formats, or confidence patterns that mocks don't capture. Still, careful integration testing with realistic mock scenarios can validate the core merge behavior.\n\nFor the full pipeline, I need to consider what could actually break: dispatching to all three reviewers might fail, result collection could timeout or return partial data, or the merge step could lose findings. Real failures would emerge at the system and agentic levels - like a reviewer hanging and timing out, or unexpected interactions between components that mocks don't reveal.\n\nTesting this adequately requires real AI calls to generate realistic outputs, actual parallel execution to surface concurrency bugs, and genuine network conditions to validate timeout handling. A real contract would expose edge cases that synthetic data misses. This clearly demands system-level testing with actual API interactions. The full behavior requires real parallel execution combined with actual AI calls orchestrated through the complete workflow. That's why Workflow testing makes sense here.\n\nLooking at confidence levels: Unit testing doesn't apply. Integration with mocks could catch dispatch and collection issues but misses timeout and concurrency problems. System-level testing with mocks handles concurrency and simulated delays but can't validate real AI output diversity. Agentic testing with real calls captures actual outputs but skips timing issues. Workflow testing with the full pipeline—real AI calls plus concurrent execution—is the only way to verify the complete behavior works end-to-end.\n\nNow reconsidering the individual behaviors. For the clause extractor identifying all key terms, I need to determine what actually constitutes a real failure in that context. The core issue is distinguishing what \"catch a real failure\" actually means. If the AI model itself fails to identify all terms in a complex contract, that's a production failure you can only surface with real AI calls—making Agentic the minimum viable approach. With mocks, you're testing whether the system handles whatever you tell it to return, not whether extraction actually works. However, there's a potential Integration path: you could maintain annotated test contracts and deliberately mock incomplete results to verify the system handles degraded extraction gracefully. But that tests resilience, not real extraction quality.\n\nThe actual failure modes split into three categories: the extractor API never gets called or returns malformed data (Integration catches these), versus the AI model itself missing key terms (only Agentic catches this). Since all three are legitimate production risks, and Agentic encompasses Integration anyway, the question becomes whether the minimum means the lowest test level that catches *any* real failure, or the lowest that catches *all* real failures.\n\nThe behavior explicitly targets identification quality—whether all key terms are found—which is fundamentally an Agentic concern. While Integration-level tests could catch infrastructure failures like API timeouts or parsing errors, those aren't what the stated behavior measures. The most probable real failure in production is the model missing terms, requiring Agentic-level validation.\n\nMy framework distinguishes based on what could actually fail: API orchestration and result handling maps to Integration; model reasoning and output quality maps to Agentic; concurrency and timing issues map to System or Workflow; and multi-step AI sequences map to Workflow.\n\nFor the merge behavior, the core failure mode is logic that loses or misattributes assessments when handling conflicts. This is primarily an Integration concern—testing the merge algorithm's correctness with conflicting inputs—though Agentic tests could help surface realistic conflict scenarios the model might generate.\n\nThe minimum infrastructure to reliably catch real failures here is Integration-level testing with mock conflicts, but production issues might only emerge when running against actual model outputs. I'm weighting Integration at 0.6, Agentic at 0.2, Unit at 0.15, and System at 0.05.\n\nActually, rereading the prompt—it's asking what's the minimum test infrastructure needed to catch a *real* failure, not just verify happy-path logic.\n\nFor the first three behaviors, the actual failure modes are all Agentic: the model might miss certain terms, fail to recognize euphemistic language, or misunderstand regulatory nuances. For the merge behavior, the real failure could be either Integration-level (logic drops assessments) or Agentic-level (real conflicting outputs break the merge), though Integration is the minimum. The final behavior's failure depends on which step breaks—could be Integration, Agentic, or a concurrency bug in parallel dispatch.\n\nThe pipeline itself requires Workflow-level testing to catch real failures, since you need end-to-end execution with actual concurrency and real AI outputs. For Behavior 4 specifically, I should reconsider whether Integration-level mocking is sufficient. If you mock reviewer outputs and test that the merge preserves both conflicting assessments with attribution, you can catch logic bugs. But real failures might only surface with actual model outputs, which Integration testing wouldn't fully expose.\n\nThe real question is whether the bug manifests with mocked data or only with production outputs. Real outputs might have unexpected JSON structures, nested conflicts that mocks don't anticipate, or confidence scores that interact with merge logic in unforeseen ways. So while Integration catches some failures, Agentic testing is needed for comprehensive coverage.\n\nSince the question asks for the minimum to catch \"a real failure\" (singular), Integration suffices for Behavior 4. But ensuring the behavior works correctly end-to-end likely requires both Integration for the merge logic and Agentic for the full pipeline. The key distinction is whether a pure in-process mock could miss the failure—if yes, then at least Integration is needed.\n\nFor Behavior 1, a mocked extractor always returns what you program it to, but a real one might miss terms, so mocks miss that failure. For Behavior 4, a mock merger with conflict scenarios can catch the merge bug, but real outputs might still fail in ways the mock doesn't anticipate. The minimum infrastructure needed depends on identifying the most likely production failure and what level of testing