RKFLOW testing at 0.45 confidence captures the full end-to-end behavior with real parallelism and model calls needed to verify findings aren't lost.\n\nFor the three AI quality behaviors, AGENTIC is the minimum level since they depend on model capability. The merge logic with conflicting inputs needs at least INTEGRATION to catch the core bug, though real failures might surface at AGENTIC when dealing with actual model outputs. The end-to-end pipeline behavior absolutely requires WORKFLOW because it demands real parallelism, actual AI calls, and orchestration across multiple steps—no lower level can validate that data flows correctly through the entire system without loss.\n\nNow reconsidering the merge behavior more carefully. The test should verify that when multiple reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments, both are preserved with proper attribution. A mock setup could catch a basic logic bug—like if merge only keeps the first assessment instead of combining them—but real reviewer outputs might have unexpected structures that only surface with actual AGENTIC calls. The minimum to catch a real failure is INTEGRATION, though discovering all possible issues might require AGENTIC.\n\nFor the confidence distribution, I'm settling on:\n- UNIT: 0.1 (basic parsing)\n- INTEGRATION: 0.55 (merge logic with mocked outputs)\n- SYSTEM: 0.05 (limited value here)\n- AGENTIC: 0.25 (real output structures)\n- WORKFLOW: 0.05 (orchestration)\n\nBehavior 5 about parallel dispatch could actually be tested at SYSTEM level with simulated delays and mocked AI, catching timeout and concurrency bugs. AGENTIC would add real AI calls but miss concurrency issues if run serially. WORKFLOW with real parallel execution catches everything, but that's overkill for just verifying the dispatch mechanism works.\n\nThe real question is whether the behavior requires actual infrastructure. Since it involves network latency from AI services, real OS-level parallelism, and non-deterministic AI responses, I need at least SYSTEM to expose the concurrency failures that only appear under real conditions. two levels, which is essentially WORKFLOW when both are necessary.\n\nLet me reconsider what WORKFLOW actually means. Looking at the definitions, it's specifically about multiple agentic steps in sequence or a complete agent pipeline—not just the combination of SYSTEM and AGENTIC testing. For Behavior 5, I have three reviewers running in parallel (AGENTIC) plus a merge step (INTEGRATION), which forms a full agent pipeline. That fits the WORKFLOW definition.\n\nBefore finalizing, I should verify that AGENTIC is truly sufficient for Behaviors 1-3. Could there be a failure mode that only SYSTEM or WORKFLOW testing would expose? Given that these behaviors involve single AI calls without complex orchestration, AGENTIC testing should be adequate to catch the relevant failure modes.\n\nFor Behavior 1 specifically—\"clause extractor identifies all key terms\"—the focus is on extraction quality, not on API reliability or integration issues. While SYSTEM-level failures like API timeouts or invalid responses are possible, the behavior itself is testing whether the extractor can actually identify the terms when it works. To validate this, I need ground truth contracts with known key terms, run the extractor against them, and verify complete identification. The test requires a contract with established key terms to measure against.\n\nAGENTIC testing is the minimum because I'm evaluating the extractor's actual capability to perform its core function. INTEGRATION could catch scenarios where the extractor isn't invoked at all, but that's not what this behavior measures. My confidence distribution reflects this: 70% for AGENTIC as the minimum level, 15% for INTEGRATION, and 5% each for the others.\n\nFor Behavior 4, I'm 55% confident INTEGRATION is the minimum since the merge logic needs to handle conflict resolution correctly—mocked inputs should expose logic errors. The remaining 25% confidence in AGENTIC accounts for cases where real outputs from the system reveal unexpected edge cases that mocks wouldn't catch.\n\nReconsidering what \"minimum\" actually means: it's the lowest level that can detect at least one genuine failure mode. INTEGRATION catches merge logic bugs, while AGENTIC catches failures from unexpected real output formats. Since INTEGRATION is lower in the stack, it's the minimum, which aligns with my probability distribution.\n\nFor Behavior 1, UNIT testing can surface parsing bugs directly. For Behavior 5, the key issue is determining what actually catches the failure. The behavior emphasizes both \"real contract\" (pointing to AGENTIC) and \"completes correctly\" in the full pipeline (pointing to WORKFLOW). Since the failure involves concurrency with real AI processing, WORKFLOW is the minimum level that catches it—you need the actual parallelism and AI quality together. My confidence distribution reflects this: WORKFLOW gets 0.45 because it's the only level catching the complete failure mode, while SYSTEM (0.2) and AGENTIC (0.2) each catch partial aspects. This means I should increase WORKFLOW's confidence significantly since it's the true minimum, pushing it toward 0.7+. The probability distribution suggests AGENTIC carries the most weight at 40%, though SYSTEM and INTEGRATION could each catch certain failures at 15%. WORKFLOW rounds out the picture at 25%, testing the complete pipeline. Given the behavior explicitly requires dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting their results, and merging them without loss for a real contract, AGENTIC seems like the intended minimum—it's the lowest level that can validate against actual AI output and real contract data.\n\nHowever, I'm realizing the behavior actually spans multiple concerns: parallel dispatch (SYSTEM), result collection and merging (INTEGRATION), and real documents (AGENTIC). Testing all three concerns together points toward WORKFLOW as the necessary level, probably around 0.60-0.70 confidence. The question becomes whether I can validate these concerns separately—a SYSTEM test could exercise real parallel dispatch with mocked AI responses and careful timing controls, while an AGENTIC test could verify behavior against actual contracts but without the full parallelism orchestration. The core issue is that catching this behavior's failures requires either SYSTEM for parallelism or AGENTIC for real contract interactions, but WORKFLOW combines both. My confidence should weight WORKFLOW highest while acknowledging that SYSTEM and AGENTIC each catch specific failure modes.\n\nSetting probabilities: UNIT gets 0.0 since it can't test the behavior at all. INTEGRATION gets 0.1 for potential merge logic issues. SYSTEM and AGENTIC each get 0.2 since they handle concurrency and AI quality respectively. WORKFLOW gets 0.5 as the most complete test covering the full pipeline. This distribution reflects that while individual test levels catch certain failures, the workflow test is most likely to be the true minimum needed.\n\nReconsidering what \"minimum level\" actually means—it's not just the lowest level that catches something, but the lowest level needed to have real confidence the behavior works in production. For this particular behavior, that requires both real parallelism and real AI interactions, which means WORKFLOW is genuinely the minimum, not INTEGRATION.\n\nI could test pieces separately—SYSTEM for concurrency without AI, AGENTIC for AI without full parallelism—but none of those individually validate the complete pipeline behavior. Only running the full workflow catches the actual failure modes that matter.\n\nMy confidence distribution reflects this: WORKFLOW at 0.6 because it's the only level that truly exercises the behavior end-to-end, with lower probabilities on the other levels acknowledging some uncertainty about whether specific failure types might be caught at lower levels.","signature":""}],"stop_rea