an AI reasoning problem about language understanding, not a logic or API problem. Only real model calls on realistic risky language will surface when the model's risk classification breaks down.","test_description":"Create test contracts containing both direct risk language ('no refund guarantee') and indirect/euphemistic equivalents ('refund terms subject to [policy]'). Configure a real risk policy. Run the risk assessor on each contract. Verify that both direct and indirect problematic language are flagged. Failure mode: model flags direct risks but misses euphemistic variants, or flags unrelated neutral language.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends entirely on the AI's knowledge of regulatory requirements for different jurisdictions. You could test that the system loads jurisdiction configs and calls the compliance checker (Integration), but that won't catch if the model's understanding of UK GDPR, US state contracts, or Singapore financial requirements is incomplete or wrong. Real regulatory compliance is an AI knowledge problem, not an orchestration problem. Only real model calls on jurisdiction-specific test contracts reveal whether the model's regulatory knowledge is accurate.","test_description":"Assemble test contracts that should pass/fail regulatory checks for multiple jurisdictions (US, EU, UK). Provide correct regulatory requirements per jurisdiction. Run the compliance checker with each jurisdiction configured. Verify the model correctly determines pass/fail status. Failure mode: model misses a regulatory requirement for certain jurisdictions, or incorrectly assesses compliance due to incomplete legal knowledge.","plan_consistent":